{"title_page": "John Weir (physician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n'''Sir John Weir''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCVO}}  (19 October 1879 &ndash; 17 April 1971) was a Scottish doctor who served as [[Physician Royal]] to several twentieth century [[monarch]]s.\n\n==Biography==\n\nBorn in the town of [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]], in [[Renfrewshire]], Scotland, Dr Weir was to become Physician Royal to [[George V|King George V]] (reigned 1910\u201336; Weir his physician from 1918), [[Edward VIII|King Edward VIII]] (reigned 1936), [[George VI|King George VI]] (reigned 1936\u201352), [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] (physician 1952\u201368), and [[Haakon VII of Norway|King Haakon VII]] (1872\u20131957) of Norway, whose wife Maud (1869\u20131938) was the youngest daughter of [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]] (1841\u20131910).\n\nWeir attended [[Allan Glen's School]] in Glasgow, a school noted for its emphasis on science. He received his medical education first at [[Glasgow University]] MB ChB 1907, and then on a sabbatical year in [[Chicago]] under the tutelage of Dr [[James Tyler Kent]] of Hering Medical College during 1908-9, along with Drs Harold Fergie Woods (1883\u20131961) and Douglas Borland (1885\u20131961).\n\nHe returned to the [[London Homeopathic Hospital]] as Consultant Physician in 1910, and was appointed the Compton-Burnett Professor of Materia Medica in 1911. He rose to become President of the Faculty of Homeopathy in 1923.\n\nWeir reputedly first learned of homeopathy through his contact with Dr Robert Gibson Miller (1862\u20131919) head of the [[NHS Centre for Integrative Care, Glasgow|Glasgow Homeopathic Hospital]], who had an important influence on the future Physician Royal, who he treated for boils and converted to homeopathy [Bodman, 1971]. \"It was Dr Gibson Miller who advised Sir John Weir to go to the United States.\" [Stewart, 1967, p.&nbsp;260] This influence tended to be passed on: Dr Douglas Gibson (1888\u20131977) \"became interested in homeopathy in 1936 through a meeting with Sir John Weir,\" [Gibson obit, 1977, 225].\n\nHe spoke on homeopathy before the [[Royal Society of Medicine]] in 1932, and was knighted by King George V that same year. The renovated [[Manchester]] Homoeopathic Institute and Dispensary was opened in Oxford Street by Sir John Weir in May 1939. Weir said in an \"address: homeopathy\u2026is no religion, no sect, no fad, no humbug\u2026remedies do not act directly on disease; they merely stimulate the vital reactions of the patient, and this causes him to cure himself.\" [Sir John Weir, 1931, 200-201] Having advanced through all levels of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] he was, as a rare distinction, awarded the [[Royal Victorian Chain]] in 1949,<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=38640|date=14 June 1949|page=2947}}</ref> possibly as a mark of the medical care he gave to the ailing King George VI.\n\n==Publications==\n*''Homeopathy and its Importance in Treatment of Chronic Disease'', (1915)\n*''The Trend of Modern Medicine'', (1922)\n*''The Science and Art of Homeopathy'', ''British Homoeopathic Journal'' (1925)\n*''The Present Day Attitude of the Medical Profession Towards Homeopathy'', ''British Homoeopathic Journal'' XVI, 1926, p.&nbsp;212ff\n*''Homeopathy: a System of Therapeutics'' (1928)\n*\"The Hahnemann Convalescent Home, Bournemouth\", ''British Homoeopathic Journal'' 20, 1931, 200-201\n*''Homeopathy: An Explanation of its Principles'' (1932)\n*\"British Homeopathy During the Last 100 Years\", ''British Homoeopathic Journal'' 23, 1932: II, pp.&nbsp;603\u20135\n*\"Samuel Hahnemann and his Influence on Medical Thought\", Trans. Roy. Soc. Med., (1933)\n*''Hahnemann on Homeopathic Philosophy'' (1935)\n\n==Sources==\n*The Medical Directory 1948\n*Nisbet's Medical Directory, 1913\n*T Fergus Stewart, Dr Tom Paterson, Brit Homeo Jnl, 56, 1967, pp.&nbsp;257\u201360\n*Obituary, ''The Times'' 19-4-1971\n*Dr [[Margery Blackie]], Obituary to Sir John Weir, Brit Homeo Jnl 60, 1971, pp.&nbsp;103\u20134\n*Dr Frank Bodman, Obituary to Sir John Weir, Brit Homeo Jnl 60:1, 1971, pp.&nbsp;224\u20138\n*Anonymous, Obituary to Dr Douglas Gibson, Brit. Homeo. Jnl 66, 1977, p.&nbsp;225\n*[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/31816 Weir's entry in the Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060715074336/http://www.drkaplan.co.uk/spec_fea/weir.htm Homeopath to Kings & Queens, a biography of Dr Weir by Dr Brian Kaplan]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weir, John}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British homeopaths]]\n[[Category:Court physicians]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:People educated at Allan Glen's School]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Victorian Chain]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n'''Sir John Weir''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|GCVO}}  (19 October 1879 &ndash; 17 April 1971) was a Scottish doctor who served as [[Physician Royal]] to several twentieth century [[monarch]]s.\n\n==Biography==\n\nBorn in the town of [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]], in [[Renfrewshire]], Scotland, Dr Weir was to become Physician Royal to [[George V|King George V]] (reigned 1910\u201336; Weir his physician from 1918), [[Edward VIII|King Edward VIII]] (reigned 1936), [[George VI|King George VI]] (reigned 1936\u201352), [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] (physician 1952\u201368), and [[Haakon VII of Norway|King Haakon VII]] (1872\u20131957) of Norway, whose wife Maud (1869\u20131938) was the youngest daughter of [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]] (1841\u20131910).\n\nWeir attended [[Allan Glen's School]] in Glasgow, a school noted for its emphasis on science. He received his medical education first at [[Glasgow University]] MB ChB 1907, and then on a sabbatical year in [[Chicago]] under the tutelage of Dr [[James Tyler Kent]] of Hering Medical College during 1908-9, along with Drs Harold Fergie Woods (1883\u20131961) and Douglas Borland (1885\u20131961).\n\nHe returned to the [[London Homeopathic Hospital]] as Consultant Physician in 1910, and was appointed the Compton-Burnett Professor of Materia Medica in 1911. He rose to become President of the Faculty of Homeopathy in 1923.\n\nWeir reputedly first learned of homeopathy through his contact with Dr Robert Gibson Miller (1862\u20131919) head of the [[NHS Centre for Integrative Care, Glasgow|Glasgow Homeopathic Hospital]], who had an important influence on the future Physician Royal, who he treated for boils and converted to homeopathy [Bodman, 1971]. \"It was Dr Gibson Miller who advised Sir John Weir to go to the United States.\" [Stewart, 1967, p.&nbsp;260] This influence tended to be passed on: Dr Douglas Gibson (1888\u20131977) \"became interested in homeopathy in 1936 through a meeting with Sir John Weir,\" [Gibson obit, 1977, 225].\n\nHe spoke on homeopathy before the [[Royal Society of Medicine]] in 1932, and was knighted by King George V that same year. The renovated [[Manchester]] Homoeopathic Institute and Dispensary was opened in Oxford Street by Sir John Weir in May 1939. Weir said in an \"address: homeopathy\u2026is no religion, no sect, no fad, no humbug\u2026remedies do not act directly on disease; they merely stimulate the vital reactions of the patient, and this causes him to cure himself.\" [Sir John Weir, 1931, 200-201] Having advanced through all levels of the [[Royal Victorian Order]] he was, as a rare distinction, awarded the [[Royal Victorian Chain]] in 1949, possibly as a mark of the medical care he gave to the ailing King George VI.\n\n==Publications==\n*''Homeopathy and its Importance in Treatment of Chronic Disease'', (1915)\n*''The Trend of Modern Medicine'', (1922)\n*''The Science and Art of Homeopathy'', ''British Homoeopathic Journal'' (1925)\n*''The Present Day Attitude of the Medical Profession Towards Homeopathy'', ''British Homoeopathic Journal'' XVI, 1926, p.&nbsp;212ff\n*''Homeopathy: a System of Therapeutics'' (1928)\n*\"The Hahnemann Convalescent Home, Bournemouth\", ''British Homoeopathic Journal'' 20, 1931, 200-201\n*''Homeopathy: An Explanation of its Principles'' (1932)\n*\"British Homeopathy During the Last 100 Years\", ''British Homoeopathic Journal'' 23, 1932: II, pp.&nbsp;603\u20135\n*\"Samuel Hahnemann and his Influence on Medical Thought\", Trans. Roy. Soc. Med., (1933)\n*''Hahnemann on Homeopathic Philosophy'' (1935)\n\n==Sources==\n*The Medical Directory 1948\n*Nisbet's Medical Directory, 1913\n*T Fergus Stewart, Dr Tom Paterson, Brit Homeo Jnl, 56, 1967, pp.&nbsp;257\u201360\n*Obituary, ''The Times'' 19-4-1971\n*Dr [[Margery Blackie]], Obituary to Sir John Weir, Brit Homeo Jnl 60, 1971, pp.&nbsp;103\u20134\n*Dr Frank Bodman, Obituary to Sir John Weir, Brit Homeo Jnl 60:1, 1971, pp.&nbsp;224\u20138\n*Anonymous, Obituary to Dr Douglas Gibson, Brit. Homeo. Jnl 66, 1977, p.&nbsp;225\n*[http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/31816 Weir's entry in the Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060715074336/http://www.drkaplan.co.uk/spec_fea/weir.htm Homeopath to Kings & Queens, a biography of Dr Weir by Dr Brian Kaplan]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Weir, John}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1971 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British homeopaths]]\n[[Category:Court physicians]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:People educated at Allan Glen's School]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Royal Victorian Chain]]\n", "name_user": "Winchester12", "label": "safe", "comment": "Citation added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Weir_(physician)"}
{"title_page": "Agi Orsi", "text_new": "Agi Orsi is an independent Los Angeles-based documentary filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/|title=Agi Orsi|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> who produces films for television and theatrical release on music and sports subcultures, as well as socially relevant themes, such as the criminalization of homelessness and the challenges of living on the street with mental illness. The subjects of her productions include river riders achieving a diplomatic triumph in a joint U-Soviet expedition, rebellious Venice skateboarders carving their separate identity in a surf-dominated culture<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/film/reviews/dogtown-and-z-boys-1200466864/|title=Dogtown and Z-Boys|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|date=Variety|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=2/11/07|access-date=}}</ref>, a courageous Hawaiian surfer remembered as the symbol of Aloha for risking his life to save others<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/archive/51471ed0c07f5d4659000002-hawaiian-the-legend-of-ed|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau|last=|first=|date=Tribeca Film Festival|website=TribecaFilm.Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, the backyard punk rock scene in East Los Angeles<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title=Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=LA Times|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> where homegrown musicians, not music conglomerates, set the tone, and struggling Skid Row homeless building community and embracing hope despite widespread despair and drug abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Lost Angels: Production Team|last=|first=|date=Cinema Libre Studio|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn addition to producing for theater and television, Orsi is a DGA Unit Production Manager on all her documentaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/filmotype/production_manager?ref_=m_nmfm_2|title=Agi Orsi: Unit Production Manager|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\n== Education ==\nA native of Budapest, Hungary, fluent in English, French and Hungarian, Orsi received her Masters in French Language and Civilization from Universit\u00e9 Panth\u00e9 on Sorbonne in Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Los Angels: Production Team|last=|first=|date=Cinema Libre Studio|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \u00a0\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nOrsi serves on the Board of Housing Works<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://housingworksca.org/team/|title=Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=Housing Works|website=Housing Works|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, a non-profit organization committed to providing supportive housing for the homeless, and participates in film forums to promote independent documentary film making and mentor aspiring documentarians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.workingfilms.org/reel-change-in-the-bay-area/|title=Reel Change: Managing Social Issue Film Campaigns|last=|first=|date=Working Films|website=Working Films|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Most Notable Awards & Recognition ==\nOrsi\u2019s foray into documentary filmmaking began when she teamed with director John Armstrong to produce '''''Bashkaus: Hard Labor in Siberia'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/bio|title=Agi Orsi Bio|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>''',''' (Discovery Channel), a film that won a '''Gold Medal Living Book Award''' and the '''Grand Prize at the Telluride Mountain Film Festival''' for chronicling the first joint US-Soviet river expedition in Russia\u2019s Altai Mountains during a thaw in the Cold War.\u00a0 Following that, Orsi teamed again with Armstrong to produce '''''Curtain of Ice''''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/curtain-of-ice/oclc/27479917|title=Curtain of Ice|last=|first=|date=World Cat|website=World Cat|url-status=live|archive-url=1992|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>(Discovery Channel), documenting the first-on water crossing of the Bering Strait, reuniting Eskimos separated for decades during the US-Russia arms escalation.\n\nMost notable is Orsi\u2019s collaboration with documentary film director and skateboarder Stacey Peralta to win '''Sundance Festival\u2019s Audience and Best Director''' award for '''''Dogtown and Z-Boys'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=(link: https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/movies/film-review-skating-on-top-of-the-world-during-an-endless-summer.html)|title=FILM REVIEW; Skating on Top of the World During an Endless Summer|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=4/26/02|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, a documentary, narrated by Sean Penn, that explores the world of skateboarding, its impact on surf culture and the disturbing aftermath of lost stardom. Orsi again teamed with Peralta to produce '''''Riding Giants''''' (Studio Canal/Sony Classics), the first documentary to ever open the Sundance Film Festival and winner of the 2004 '''A.C.E. Eddie Award''' for '''Best Edited Documentary''' by editor Paul Crowder. In Riding Giants director Stacy Peralta's pays tribute to the adventurous surfers riding the world's most daunting 20-foot high waves, only to yearn for even more challenging thrill rides. \n\nAdditionally Orsi worked with director and professional surfer Sam George to produce '''''Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau''''' (ESPN''''')'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/espn-films-30-30-hawaiian-154949024.html|title=ESPN Films: \"30 for 30\" \"Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau\" Wins Emmy Award|last=|first=|date=Yahoo Finance/Marketwired|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=May 29, 2014|access-date=}}</ref>''',''' a biographical film of a big wave surfer, the symbol of Aloha, that premiered on [[ESPN]] on October 1, 2013 and won an '''Emmy for Best Sports Documentary Series''', making it one of the few surf-related films to ever receive such recognition. The documentary that chronicle's Aikau's emergence as a premier surfer and lifeguard who saved lives but was lost at sea during a rescue effort, also won awards for '''Best Picture and Best Director at the Malibu International Film Festival'''; '''Best Picture, Best Documentary and Audience Favorite at the Maui Film Festival''', as well as '''Best Documentary at Surfer Poll'''.\n\nDeparting from the adventure sports genre, Orsi served as supervising producer on '''''Amazing Journey: The Story of The Who'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0462441/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Amazing Journey: The Story of the Who|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, a 2007 documentary '''''nominated for a Grammy''' '''Award''''', co-directed by [[Murray Lerner]] and [[Paul Crowder (filmmaker)|Paul Crowder]] integrating archival footage of The Who's concerts with interviews of the English band. The film's soundtrack features a compilation of the band's greatest hits. Included in the documentary is original footage, never seen before, of the 1970 Leeds University appearance in which The WHO's performance disintegrated into \"chaotic noise\" as a result of amphetamine use, resulting in a fist fight between band members and the temporary expulsion of lead singer Roger Daltrey.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n\n'''''Los Punks; We Are All We Have''''' (2016)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Angela Boatwright\n\n[Official Selection: Slamdance Film Festival, East End Film Festival]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title=Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=Los Angeles Times|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=May 26, 2016|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n\n'''''Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau''''' (2013)\u2014 Documentary Feature, dir. Sam George\n\n[Winner: Emmy Award for Best Sports Documentary Series]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 ESPN \u201830 for 30\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/archive/51471ed0c07f5d4659000002-hawaiian-the-legend-of-ed|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddi Aikau|last=|first=|date=Tribeca Film Festival|website=Tribeca Film. Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''No Room for Rockstars''''' (2012)\u2014 Documentary Feature of the 2010 Warped Tour, dir. Parris Patton\n\n[Official Selection: Slamdance Film Festival, Hot Docs]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1996339/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=No Room for Rock Stars (Full Cast and Crew)|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Lost Angels: Skid Row is my Home''''' (2010)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Thomas Napper\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Los Angels: Production Crew|last=|first=|date=Cinema Libre|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n \n\n\n'''''Amazing Journey: The Story of the Who''''' (2007)\u2014 Documentary Feature, \n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Spitfire Films/Universal Pictures \u00a0 \u200bdir. Paul Crowder, Murray Lerner<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0462441/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Amazing Journey: Story of the Who  (Full Cast and Crew)|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n'''''Riding Giants''''' (2004)\u2014 Documentary Feature, dir. Stacy Peralta\n\n[Opener: Sundance Film Festival]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Studio Canal\n\n\n'''''Dogtown and Z-Boys''''' (2001)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Stacy Peralta\n\n[Winner: Sundance Audience Award, Sundance Directing Award]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Sony Pictures Classics <ref>{{Cite web|url=(link: https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/movies/film-review-skating-on-top-of-the-world-during-an-endless-summer.html)|title=Review: Skating on Top of the World|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=New York Times|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=4/26/02|access-date=}}</ref> \n\n\n'''''Bashkaus: Hard Labor in Siberia''''' (1990)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. John Armstrong\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions/Discovery Channel\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<br />\n", "text_old": "Agi Orsi is an independent Los Angeles-based documentary filmmaker<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/|title=Agi Orsi|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> who produces films for television and theatrical release on music and sports subcultures, as well as socially relevant themes, such as the criminalization of homelessness and the challenges of living on the street with mental illness. The subjects of her productions include the diplomatic triumph of a joint U-Soviet river expedition, rebellious Venice skateboarders carving their separate identity in a surf-dominated culture<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2001/film/reviews/dogtown-and-z-boys-1200466864/|title=Dogtown and Z-Boys|last=Harvey|first=Dennis|date=Variety|website=Variety|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=2/11/07|access-date=}}</ref>, a courageous Hawaiian surfer remembered as the symbol of Aloha for risking his life to save others, the backyard punk rock scene in East Los Angeles<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title=Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=LA Times|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> where homegrown musicians, not music conglomerates, set the tone, and struggling Skid Row homeless building community and embracing hope despite widespread despair and drug abuse.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Lost Angels: Production Team|last=|first=|date=Cinema Libre Studio|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \n\nIn addition to producing for theater and television, Orsi is a DGA Unit Production Manager on all her documentaries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.imdb.com/name/nm0650709/filmotype/production_manager?ref_=m_nmfm_2|title=Agi Orsi: Unit Production Manager|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>  \n\n== Education ==\nA native of Budapest, Hungary, fluent in English, French and Hungarian, Orsi received her Masters in French Language and Civilization from Universit\u00e9 Panth\u00e9 on Sorbonne in Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cinemalibrestudio.com/skidrowismyhome/production_team.html|title=Los Angels: Production Team|last=|first=|date=Cinema Libre Studio|website=Cinema Libre Studio|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> \u00a0\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nOrsi serves on the Board of Housing Works<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://housingworksca.org/team/|title=Board of Directors|last=|first=|date=Housing Works|website=Housing Works|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, a non-profit organization committed to providing supportive housing for the homeless, and participates in film forums to promote independent documentary film making and mentor aspiring documentarians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.workingfilms.org/reel-change-in-the-bay-area/|title=Reel Change: Managing Social Issue Film Campaigns|last=|first=|date=Working Films|website=Working Films|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Most Notable Awards & Recognition ==\nOrsi\u2019s foray into documentary filmmaking began when she teamed with director John Armstrong to produce '''''Bashkaus: Hard Labor in Siberia'',''' (Discovery Channel), a film that won a '''Gold Medal Living Book Award''' and the '''Grand Prize at the Telluride Mountain Film Festival''' for chronicling the first joint US-Soviet river expedition in Russia\u2019s Altai Mountains during a thaw in the Cold War.\u00a0 Following that, Orsi teamed again with Armstrong to produce '''''Curtain of Ice''''' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/curtain-of-ice/oclc/27479917|title=Curtain of Ice|last=|first=|date=World Cat|website=World Cat|url-status=live|archive-url=1992|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>(Discovery Channel), documenting the first-on water crossing of the Bering Strait, reuniting Eskimos separated for decades during the US-Russia arms escalation.\n\nMost notable is Orsi\u2019s collaboration with documentary film director and skateboarder Stacey Peralta to win '''Sundance Festival\u2019s Audience and Best Director''' award for '''''Dogtown and Z-Boys'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=(link: https://www.nytimes.com/2002/04/26/movies/film-review-skating-on-top-of-the-world-during-an-endless-summer.html)|title=FILM REVIEW; Skating on Top of the World During an Endless Summer|last=Holden|first=Stephen|date=4/26/02|website=New York Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, a documentary, narrated by Sean Penn, that explores the world of skateboarding, its impact on surf culture and the disturbing aftermath of lost stardom. Orsi again teamed with Peralta to produce '''''Riding Giants''''' (Studio Canal/Sony Classics), the first documentary to ever open the Sundance Film Festival and winner of the 2004 '''A.C.E. Eddie Award''' for '''Best Edited Documentary''' by editor Paul Crowder. In Riding Giants director Stacy Peralta's pays tribute to the adventurous surfers riding the world's most daunting 20-foot high waves, only to yearn for even more challenging thrill rides. \n\nAdditionally Orsi worked with director and professional surfer Sam George to produce '''''Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau''''' (ESPN''''')'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/espn-films-30-30-hawaiian-154949024.html|title=ESPN Films: \"30 for 30\" \"Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau\" Wins Emmy Award|last=|first=|date=Yahoo Finance/Marketwired|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=May 29, 2014|access-date=}}</ref>''',''' a biographical film of a big wave surfer, the symbol of Aloha, that premiered on [[ESPN]] on October 1, 2013 and won an '''Emmy for Best Sports Documentary Series''', making it one of the few surf-related films to ever receive such recognition. The documentary that chronicle's Aikau's emergence as a premier surfer and lifeguard who saved lives but was lost at sea during a rescue effort, also won awards for '''Best Picture and Best Director at the Malibu International Film Festival'''; '''Best Picture, Best Documentary and Audience Favorite at the Maui Film Festival''', as well as '''Best Documentary at Surfer Poll'''.\n\nDeparting from the adventure sports genre, Orsi served as supervising producer on '''''Amazing Journey: The Story of The Who'''''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0462441/fullcredits/?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm|title=Amazing Journey: The Story of the Who|last=|first=|date=IMDB|website=IMDB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, a 2007 documentary '''''nominated for a Grammy''' '''Award''''', co-directed by [[Murray Lerner]] and [[Paul Crowder (filmmaker)|Paul Crowder]] integrating archival footage of The Who's concerts with interviews of the English band. The film's soundtrack features a compilation of the band's greatest hits. Included in the documentary is original footage, never seen before, of the 1970 Leeds University appearance in which The WHO's performance disintegrated into \"chaotic noise\" as a result of amphetamine use, resulting in a fist fight between band members and the temporary expulsion of lead singer Roger Daltrey.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n\n'''''Los Punks; We Are All We Have''''' (2016)\u2014 Documentary feature, dir. Angela Boatwright\n\n[Official Selection: Slamdance Film Festival, East End Film Festival]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 Agi Orsi Productions <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/la-et-los-punks-movie-20160525-snap-story.html|title=Los Punks\u2019 documentary goes behind the scenes of L.A.'s underground punk rock scene|last=Roberts|first=Randall|date=Los Angeles Times|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=May 26, 2016|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n\n'''''Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddie Aikau''''' (2013)\u2014 Documentary Feature, dir. Sam George\n\n[Winner: Emmy Award for Best Sports Documentary Series]\n\n\u25ca Producer\u2014 ESPN \u201830 for 30\u2019<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribecafilm.com/festival/archive/51471ed0c07f5d4659000002-hawaiian-the-legend-of-ed|title=Hawaiian: The Legend of Eddi Aikau|last=|first=|date=Tribeca Film Festival|website=Tribeca Film. Com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n\n\n'''''No Room for Rockstars''''' (2012)\u2014 Documentary Feature of the 2010 Warped Tour, dir. 